body: Contrib Operators are not custom kernels. Contrib operators are schemas that are statically linked into onnxruntime.dll. Normally their implementations are also linked to the core runtime in such a way. Custom kernels are implementations of some operator schemas in separated DLLs. You may implement a contrib operator schema in such a way, but normally we think Contrib ops and contrib ops are not related as their kernel interfaces are very different.
If they are already in the main DLL, then they are. If not,  then no way.

@snnn 

Please kindly share where do I find contributed operators that are already part of the main DLL and those which are not. 

I would like to learn how to tract those which are in and those which are not.

Question

What is the benefit of having the listed contributed operators and yet not including them in the Main Dll?
@GeorgeS2019 Can you email me at natalie.kershaw@microsoft.com and I can share this information with you

#### Examples of pre/post CustomOps as a shared library
> Through further offline communication, it seems the Onnx team has started to create packages for this library

##### Deep Vision: pre/post processing CustomOps
- [x] [OpenCV Image Decoder & SuperResolution CustomOps](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-extensions/pull/295)

##### Deep NLP: pre/post processing CustomOps

> Reference: [[Feature Request] Classify Contributed Ops](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13084)
> The priority will be those Ops that are not related to tokenization BUT perform post-processing operations such as

##### nlp
com.microsoft.nlp
- [com.microsoft.nlp.BeamSearch](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md#com.microsoft.BeamSearch)
- [com.microsoft.nlp.GreedySearch](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md#com.microsoft.GreedySearch)

body:
The contrib ops are listed here: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md
These are all included and packaged as part of the release binaries.

I do not think we should expose them as a separate entity. This is not a supportable pubic interface. We use it for optimization purposes and some other internal needs. It is important that we are able to innovate freely when outside the standard boundaries.

issue.body:
#### Original title
C# : how I can innovate the language generation in onnx gpt-2 model with the beam search and/or other custom operators of similar class (Deep NLP)

### Describe the feature request

[how I can stop or truncate the generation in onnx gpt-2 model with the beam search option](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13088) provides an **unmet** Deep NLP use case, especially langauge generation.

Currently, early stopping needs to be enabled with appropriately generated eos token to customize BeamSearch results



### Describe scenario use case

The [feedback ](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13088#issuecomment-1264791404)from user suggests additional ways to customize BeamSearch is needed to provide more optimum language generation results.

This is just with BeamSearch, how about other Contributed Operators of similar class? e.g. GreedySearch discussed in [Classify Contributed Ops ](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13084)

##### nlp
com.microsoft.nlp
- [com.microsoft.nlp.BeamSearch](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md#com.microsoft.BeamSearch)
- [com.microsoft.nlp.GreedySearch](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md#com.microsoft.GreedySearch)
